Breast Cancer

Claudio Palmeri, Pietro Sittoni
23/09/2022

Introduction



This dataset was created by Dr. William H. Wolberg.


Each records represent a sample of breast tumor masses sampled using Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA).

Sample of FNA

The dataset

The dataset is composed by 32 columns and 569 row where each column represents:

  • Id of the patient

  • Status of the patient

  • Ten real-valued features of the tumor cells computed from the analysis of a gray-scaled image:
    • radius
    • texture
    • perimeter
    • area
    • smoothness
    • compactness
    • concavity
    • concave points
    • symmetry
    • fractal dimension

Produced 3 quantities: mean, standard error, worst cases.

Summary

  • In general cancer cells have higher values more frequently than benign ones

We decided to try to predict the diagnosis of a tumor by using all the other features present in the dataset.

This is a binary classification problem.

Classification

We implemented 3 different models in order to succeed in our task:

  • Logistic regression

  • LDA

  • QDA

We also randomly divided our dataset in 2 parts:

  • 80% of the observation were used as a training set
  • 20% as the validation set

Logistic regression

The fitting algorithm did not converge and all predictor p-value was almost one so we did a constraint-based backward stepwise selection. We were left with 8 predictors and are the following:

  • mean concavity
  • radius standard error
  • texture standard error
  • compactness standard error
  • number of concave points standard error
  • worst cases radius
  • worst cases texture
  • worst cases symmetry

LDA

By implementing linear discriminant analysis (LDA) we got the following metrics and confusion matrix as a measure of our performances:

        1  1 40

4 Specificity 0.98550725
5 Neg.pred.V. 0.93150685

QDA

Similarly as before by implementing quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) we got the following metrics and confusion matrix as a measure of our performances:
